@page "/install"
@layout MainLayout

<article class="install-page">
    <div class="page-container">

        <header class="page-header">
            <h2>Set Up Tovik in Minutes</h2>
            <p class="subheader">Want your website to greet visitors in their preferred language? Tovik makes it easy. You can get started with just one line of code—and go as advanced as you like from there.</p>
        </header>

        <section class="step-1">
            <header>
                <aside>Step 1</aside>
                <h3>Turn On Automatic Translation</h3>
            </header>
            <div>
                <p>
                    Make your site instantly adapt to each visitor’s language—no coding skills required.<br />
                    Add this line right before the closing <span>&lt;&sol;body&gt;</span> tag of your site’s HTML:
                </p>
                <div class="code-container">
                    <CodeBlock CanCopy=true>
                        <script type="module" src="https://engine.sparc.coop/Tovik-translate.js"></script>
                    </CodeBlock>
                </div>
                <p>
                    That’s it. Tovik will now detect your visitors’ browser language and display your site accordingly.                    
                </p>
                <ul>
                    <li>One line of code</li>
                    <li>No setup dashboard</li>
                    <li>No API keys</li>
                    <li>No stress</li>
                </ul>
                <p>
                    If that’s all you need, you’re good to go. But if you want to give users more control or tailor what gets translated, keep reading.
                </p>
            </div>
        </section>

        <section class="step-2">
            <header>
                <aside>Step 2 (recommended)</aside>
                <h3>Let Visitors Choose Their Language</h3>
            </header>
            <div>
                <p>Automatic is great, but choice is better. Adding a language selector gives your visitors full control—especially helpful if their browser settings don’t reflect their actual language preference.</p>
                <p>To add a dropdown language picker to your page, insert this wherever you want it to appear:</p>
                <div class="code-container">
                    <CodeBlock CanCopy=true>
                        <Tovik-langselect></Tovik-langselect>
                    </CodeBlock>
                </div>
                <p>
                    It comes pre-loaded with supported languages and behaves like a regular HTML element, so you can customize the look to match your brand. Here’s some starter CSS:
                </p>
                <div class="code-container">
                    <CodeBlock CanCopy=true>
                        Tovik-langselect {
                        appearance: none; /* Removes default styling */
                        background-color: #f9f9f9;
                        color: #333;
                        padding: 10px 14px;
                        border: 1px solid #ccc;
                        border-radius: 6px;
                        font-size: 16px;
                        font-family: sans-serif;}
                    </CodeBlock>
                </div>
            </div>
        </section>

        <section>
            <header>
                <aside>Step 3 (optional)</aside>
                <h3>Choose What Gets Translated</h3>
            </header>
            <div>
                <p>
                    By default, Toviks the whole page. But if you want more control, you can specify exactly which sections should (or shouldn’t) be translated.
                </p>
                <p>To target a specific section, use:</p>
                <div class="code-container">
                    <CodeBlock CanCopy=true>
                        <Tovik-translate for="{selector}"></Tovik-translate>
                    </CodeBlock>
                </div>
                <p>Where <span class="code-text">&lcub;selector&rcub;</span></p>
                <p>You can include multiple <span>&lt;Tovik-translate&gt;</span> tags as well, if you have multiple separate sections you wish to translate.</p>
                <h4>Examples:</h4>
                <p>To translate an element with an ID of translate-this:</p>
                <CodeBlock>
                    <Tovik-translate for="#translate-this"></Tovik-translate>
                </CodeBlock>
                <p>To translate all elements with the CSS class .translate</p>
                <CodeBlock>
                    <Tovik-translate for=".translate"></Tovik-translate>
                </CodeBlock>
            </div>
        </section>

        <section class="step-4">
            <header>
                <aside>Step 4 (Advanced)</aside>
                <h3>Keep Translations Live</h3>
            </header>
            <div>
                <p>
                    If your site updates dynamically—like a chat, dashboard, or app—Tovik can keep translations up to date in real time.
                    <br/>
                    Just add the <span class="code-text">live</span> attribute like this:
                </p>
                <div class="code-container">
                    <CodeBlock CanCopy=true>
                        <Tovik-translate for="#app" live></Tovik-translate>
                    </CodeBlock>
                </div>
                <p>This keeps translations fresh as new content appears.</p>
                <p>Most static websites won't need this.</p>
                <h4>That's It</h4>
                <p>
                    Whether you want plug-and-play simplicity or more control, Tovik is built to meet you where you are—no developer required.
                </p>
            </div>
        </section>

    </div>
</article>

